node.text:
Inspiration to make the house look extra special this Christmas came from @stgermainuk and @hedgesandflowers. They collaborated on an absolutely beautiful festive gift set, the Winter Bloom Bauble and Spritz Kit.
⠀
You get four gorgeous handmade glass baubles with real dried flowers inside (by the brilliant @hedgesandflowers), art-deco glasses, carafe, and jigger. The St-Germain bottle itself is the most handsome bottle in the history of handsome bottles.
⠀
⠀
The kits on hedgesandflowers.com are an absolute a steal at £40 (I was going to buy a kit as a gift for my sister, but she saw this video and bought one for herself).
⠀
After decorating the tree, I made myself a little St-Germain Spritz – that's St-Germain elderflower liqueur, prosecco, soda water, and a twist of lemon – the perfect Christmassy indulgence.

node.text: What’s your favourite season? Mine is whichever season we’re in right at the start of it, but toward the end I’d always say autumn. It has rained all day here. Looking out the window, it doesn’t look like the middle of summer. But I sort of like it, because I’m at that point in the season where I start to look forward to the next one. I’m pining after big jumpers and roaring fires and hearty stews. Anyone else the same?

node.text:
(Ad) When I first started out, I spent a year learning traditional photography. I loved working in the darkroom, seeing all these shapes and shadows gradually appear on the page, like they were moving, like magic. It was good to have a physical object to hold in my hand, to take that object home, put it up on the wall, and share it with people.
⠀
These days, I don't often get to hold physical copies of my work. But yesterday morning I opened a package from @inkifi_instagram. It was a dozen square prints of my photos and I felt the same buzz I felt all those years ago seeing my work in print for the first time. I must've looked at these photos hundreds of times on my phone and laptop, but looking at them in print was like seeing them fresh. I remembered all the details of the day: who I was with, where we were, what we were doing… how Lenny really hated that headdress and savagely chewed it to shreds seconds after the photo was taken.
⠀
That’s what printing our photos does, I think: it brings memories to life, like magic. And now is a good time to bring a bit of magic into our homes.

node.text: My favourite thing about Instagram insights is the follower location. By city, most of my followers are in London, Hong Kong, Taipei, Paris and New York (in that order). How cool is that?! I’m a total nerd for looking at maps, but I know there’ll always be loads of places I’ve never even heard of. Let’s play a game: say hello and tell us where in the world you are right now! (*disclaimer: I’m not currently sat on the beach with a mirror. I’m at home in my big fluffy dressing gown with a cup of tea ready to say hello to you all 👀)

node.text: (#sponsored). Three of my favourite things: books, coffee and, cinemagraphs. Mind you, cinemagraphs would also make the list of my three least favourite things… I haven’t made one for a while, but I recently went to a cinemagraph workshop with @taylors & @creatingforgood. Making cinemagraphs usually ends in me wanting to smash up my laptop. But after the workshop, I felt inspired to have another crack at making the perfect seamless loop. I also brought home a load of @taylors coffee. My faves are: Rich Italian and Fika.  This is actually my third attempt at posting this video (I’m sure some of you saw my first two attempts yesterday 😳🙊), but the quality was really crap. Right, I’m off to smash up my laptop ...

node.text: (#sponsored) What would you do for love? Well, there's not much I wouldn't do for my green gang. I tolerate the gnats they attract. I get my hands dirty potting and repotting them. I do a morning and nighttime role call to make sure they're all fed and watered and get lots of light. But they give back by making my house look pretty, cleaning the air, and cheering me up. I really do love the little buggers. For everybody who posts a picture responding to the question, using hashtag #DiorLoveChain, @diorparfums will donate money to @wemovement, which helps communities lift themselves out of poverty. I'm nominating @monalogue, @sarah_louise_ferg, @beautelicieuse, @alexandriaslens and @jessicarosewilliams.

node.text:
(AD) On the road with @away.
⠀
One of my favourite road books is Travels With Charlie by John Steinbeck. There's a bit where Steinbeck remembers a town as having America's most dramatic weather, the hottest heatwaves, the heaviest snows… He drives through this town and the weather's very mild, very undramatic. Steinbeck stops, sits down among tall trees, and has another little think about the town: he still remembers it as having the hottest heatwaves, the heaviest snows. "I am happy to report that in the war between reality and romance," he says, "reality is not the stronger."
⠀
Steinbeck is accused of invention, of making up parts of his book. I don't care. Travel is all about invention: invention is how you pick where to go, what to do when you get there, and what stories to tell when you get back – stories about the weather being the best weather, the food being the nicest food, the people being the best, nicest people in the whole wide world…
⠀
Steinbeck's trip is 10,000 miles. My trip, in reality, is an hour away from home. It doesn't matter, it's all the same – the weather is perfect, these trees are the best, nicest trees… And the reality of travel is nothing without romance 🥰
⠀
⠀

⠀

node.text:
(AD) "Travel," Anthony Bourdain said, "is about the gorgeous feeling of teetering in the unknown." That feeling's at its strongest, I think, when you're planning your next trip.
⠀
You get the maps out. You make your lists, places you'd like to go, things you'd like to do, what you're going to eat. You pick clothes to travel in. You count down the days and you count down the days until, finally, most excitingly, you fetch the case from the cupboard and you pack.
⠀
I've been travelling with my @away luggage for a good few years now. It's starting to get that lovely lived-in look, well-used, well-loved, exactly how luggage is meant to look. You can tell it’s been out on the road. Every time I fetch my case from the cupboard I get a little rush, a little thrill in my tummy, that gorgeous felling of teetering in the unknown 🥰
⠀
⠀

node.text:
(Ad) Lighting a fairytale scene with @pookylights 💗
⠀
Pooky asked me to make a little video about their absolutely beautiful range of rechargeable lamps. The charge lasts for ages, and they're cordless, so I took my Phileas lamp to one of my favourite places in the world, The Grot in the Lake District. Doesn't the cosy colour of the light just look the prettiest in there? But I've got a better story to tell you about why I love these lamps…
⠀
I got home late one night last week. It was right in the middle of a storm, freezing cold, and winter dark. I turned on the hallway light and the lightswitch clicked that hollow click, nothing happened, no light: we'd had a powercut.
⠀
Now, I have to admit, I don't react well in these situations. My imagination runs wild. I'm prone to panic. So I built a wood fire to prevent hypothermia, made coffee on the gas burner to stay alert to danger, and brought Lenny's bed into the living room so he could works shifts as guard dog. I remained calm – I definitely didn't panic one little bit – by reading my book in the lovely warm light of my Pooky lamp.
⠀
I was already madly in love with these lamps – I have mine in the corner of the living room on a night, then move it through to the bedroom at bedtime as my bedside reading light – but our relationship was really consummated that night during the powercut. I also think these @pookylights lamps make the best christmas present: they're really beautiful and they're very handy in both panicky and non-panicky situations 😁🥰
⠀

(Ad) Bringing memories to life with the the Moments Frame by @inkifi_instagram. 
⠀
I've worked with Inkifi for years now – because you just can't beat having proper quality prints of your photos. The Moments Frame holds 52 photos, a memory for each week of the year.
⠀
Virginia Woolf wrote a good thing about memory: "the most ordinary movement in the world," she said, "may agitate a thousand odd, disconnected fragments, now bright, now dim, hanging and bobbing and dipping and flaunting."
⠀
I've looked at the photos in my Moments Frame countless times on my phone and laptop. But looking at them in print feels like looking at them for the first time. I see the Wee White House in Glenco and The Grot at Rydal, but I remember a thousand odd, disconnected fragments, all the details of the day, who I was with, what we ate, where we had coffee, the music we listened to in the car, lovely memories of lovely moments, the ones that do all the bobbing and dipping and flaunting ❤️
⠀

(Ad) wandering around a wintery, christmassy Edinburgh with @tommyhilfiger 🥰
⠀
There's this lovely bit in The Great Gatsby where the narrator remembers going home for Christmas, remembers the "street lamps and sleigh bells" and "chatter of frozen breath" and "fur coats of the girls," familiar things that make him feel really at home.
⠀
I post pictures of Edinburgh so often you lot think it's my home. You're sort of right. My dad's from Edinburgh. I would go with my sisters to stay with our Edinburgh family most holidays, and I loved it, especially Christmastime.
⠀
I was over the moon when @tommyhilfiger invited me to their new Edinburgh shop in the St James Quarter, kitted me out with a cosy scarf, cosier jumper, and the cosiest faux fur coat in the history of cosy faux fur coats, then sent me out on a wander to make a little video of the city getting ready for Christmas.
⠀
So here it is, Edinburgh looking its wintery, christmassy best, Edinburgh looking exactly how I remember it, the street lamps and sleigh bells and frozen breath and fur coats, familiar things that make me feel really at home ❤️
⠀
⠀

(Ad) Where do you get your best ideas?
⠀
I reckon you shouldn't go looking for an idea; let the idea come to you. Ideas usually find me when I'm out walking – ideally somewhere like this, among my beloved giant redwoods.
⠀
For Adobe MAX, @adobe invited me to work with amazing artists from all over the world on a series of pictures representing the various stages of the creative process. The theme is "creating with joy". My stage is all about ideas.
⠀
I tried to make a little rhyme of the sunlight through the trees and the sunflowers in my hands – because, you know, the one feeds the other, the seed of your idea grows and flowers into your finished project… (😳) Honestly, I could bang on about this stuff all day!
⠀
The thing you make never ever lives up to the idea in your head. But that's what I like best about the creative process – the trying, the overreaching, the making-a-big-massive-mess-of-it, the trying again… If all else fails, I go and have a nice long walk among my beloved giant redwoods. They've always got the right idea.
⠀
I've put a link in my bio so you can see the rest of the images and read a bit more about our project. All the amazing talks and workshops from this year's Adobe MAX are now online to watch free.
⠀
#AdobePartner #AdobeMAX

(Ad) A cosy, rainy autumn Sunday at home with @penhaligons_london.
⠀
Autumn has really made itself known this morning. Rain tapping on the window. Reds, golds, and golden brown leaves blowing about outside. And the day's pleasantly dark, a good excuse to get the fire blazing, the coffee brewing, and the candles flickering.
⠀
As well as being my most-loved perfume people since forever, @penhaligons_london also make the best candles in the whole entire history of candles. If I had to pick a favourite from this setup, I'd probably go for the woody, smoky, leathery Maduro Leaf (the black one), but they're all really beautiful. They had the whole house smelling amazing before I even lit them.
⠀
How's Sunday shaping up for you?
